 ÉÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ»
 º±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±  Introduction  ±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±º
 ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼

  As you likely know, one of TNM 7's new killer features is its ability
  to incorporate plugins into the mix.

  This is a new experience for all of us - you as the developers who want
  to see their programs work with TNM 7 and me, the person having to write
  the plugin interface as a whole and the accompanying documentation.

  There's one thing I want to clear up before we get started: TNM 7's
  Plugin Interface is far from being static. It will certainly be changed
  over the weeks and months to come.

  At the moment, all plugins are invoked by opening a special menu and
  selecting a plugin. My goal is to eventually allow for plugins to create
  new match types which integrate into TNM 7 like the built-in matches do.

  Mike Sweetser, for instance, is currently working on a Brawl For All
  plugin. As of this writing, when invoking the plugin, you need to enter
  the names of the two wrestlers you want to pit against one another.

  Eventually, I see the "Brawl For All" match being an option on the match
  scheduling screen - which means the plugin will be "fed" its data in a form
  where no additional user interaction is necessary for the match to begin.



