 º±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±  Where We Are  ±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±º
 ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼

  The current Plugin Interface version is 1.1.

  TNM 7 is organized in the following way:

    * PROGRAM:  contains all program files
    * DATA:     contains all data files
    * PLUGINS:  contains all plugin .INF-files and the directories which
                host the actual plugin programs

  In addition, TNM 7 has a directory for every existing circuit.

  There are two different types of plugins, regular plugins and so-called
  "circuit plugins".

  The main differences are their purpose and the place where they are
  executed. A circuit plugin usually performs an action which is sensible
  at circuit-level only, e.g. a logfile formatter. Running such a plugin
  outside of a circuit makes no sense. The opposite is true for regular
  plugins. What would the purpose of running the TNM 7 Diagnostics Utility
  in a circuit directory be ?

  When TNM 7 is started up, it's running in the TNM 7 root directory, i.e.
  the directory containing the PROGRAM, DATA and PLUGINS directories.

  This is the same environment in which regular plugins run. Of TNM 7's
  program code, only the main progam and the TNM ControlCenter run in this
  environment.

  Once you switch over to a circuit, TNM 7 starts running in the circuit's
  directory (e.g. C:\TNM7\WWF). While this doesn't sound like a biggie, it
  is. As soon as you move away from TNM 7's root directory, all file
  locations change.

  For instance, before entering a circuit, the wrestler database could be
  accessed by opening DATA\WRESTLRS.DAT (more info on this later). Once you're
  in a circuit, the path is ..\DATA\WRESTLRS.DAT.

  The same goes for every other file. While a circuit plugin has to access
  TNM 7's configuration file by opening ..\TNM.CNF, a regular plugin will
  find it by opening TNM.CNF.

  You have to make up your mind concerning what kind of plugin you want to
  write *before* coding the first line. The first step *always* is to
  decide what kind of a plugin to make.

  Will you plugin be more useful as a general tool or rather on a circuit
  level ?

  Once that decision has been made, you can start coding.

  Some examples for accessing files as a regular plugin or as a circuit
  plugin:

