 ÉÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ»
 º±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±  Plugin Developing Guidelines  ±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±º
 ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼

  All plugins are called in a uniform way by TNM 7's Plugin Interface 1.1:

    plugin_executable plugin_program_directory plugin_data_directory

  Example (circuit plugin named PLUGTEST.EXE):

    ..\PLUGINS\PLUGTEST\PLUGTEST.EXE C:\TNM7\PLUGINS\PLUGTEST C:\TNM7\PLUGINS\PLUGTEST\DATA

  That means your program will be passed two parameters via the command
  line:

  a) its program directory
     -> you need this to access any resource files your program comes with,
        for instance bitmaps and compile-time data files
     -> to access these files, you simply need to take the resource's
        location relative to your program file (e.g. BITMAPS\BITMAP1.BMP)
        and append it to the program directory passed through the command
        line (don't forget to put a "\" between the parts !), giving you
        C:\TNM7\PLUGINS\PLUGTEST\BITMAPS\BITMAP1.BMP - which is the location
        where your resource will be found
     -> under no circumstances should you hardcode any paths into your
        program; always use the plugin_program_directory variable and the
        relative location of your resource !
  b) its data directory
     -> this is the ONLY place your plugin is allowed to write its data to !
     -> it is your job to make sure the data directory exists before writing
        files to it; create it if it doesn't exist

  There are certain restrictions that we place on you, the plugin developers.
  Exceptions from these restrictions may be granted on a case-by-case basis.

  1. Your plugins must not write data anywhere but in the directory passed
     via the command line. In particular, we absolutely forbid write access
     to any of TNM 7's data files. Exceptions may be granted if you really
     know what you're doing. Ask first, though.
  2. Your plugins must clear the screen on exit.
  3. In order to turn your programs into true plugins, you need to send them
     to copp@tnm7.com. You will then receive an authorization file for each
     of them (*.INF). TNM 7 will not accept your programs as plugins without
     those files.

  In addition to these restrictions, there are certain recommendations we
  make:

  1. All text-mode plugins should display a center-aligned copyright notice
     in the last line of the screen, white (color 15) on dark red (color 4).
  2. If your plugin creates any temporary files, always delete them before
     exiting.
  3. If necessary, add some kind of documentation to your plugin and make it
     accessible from the program.

  You are not limited in any way when it comes to the programming language
  you want to use. TNM 7 allows you to create your plugins in any language
  which can generate EXE-files.

  QBASIC won't do because its files come as source code. Source code files
  can not be used as TNM 7 plugins !


