  1. CARD.LGS:
  ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
    Purpose:
      Contains the names and locations of all your circuits

    Structure:
      circuit_name 1
      circuit_directory 1

      circuit_name 2
      circuit_directory 2

      ...

    Example:
      WWF Circuit
      WWF

      WCW Circuit
      WCW


    Additional Information:
      One record consists of three lines, the two shown above and an
      empty line; this empty line has to be there although it isn't used
      anymore. It used to host the logo to be shown when entering the
      circuit. This feature was cut when TNM V6.0 was released since it
      only worked in DOS and fullscreen Windows.


  2. TNM.BUI:
  ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
    Purpose:
      Contains the names and locations of all your backups

    Structure:
      backup_filename 1
      compression method [zip or empty] 1
      backup_name 1
      date at which the backup was generated 1
      backup_filename 2
      compression method [zip or empty] 2
      backup_name 2
      date at which the backup was generated 2
      ...

    Example:
      BACKUP_Z.TBU
      zip
      Test Backup
      07-09-1998
      BACK~001.TBU
      zip
      Before importing Robert's stuff
      07-10-1998
      BACK~002.TBU
      zip
      Before deleting doubles
      07-10-1998

    Additional Information:
      One record consists of four lines as shown above. The backup's filename
      is relative to the BACKUP directory.


  3. TNM.CNF:
  ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
    Purpose:
      TNM 7 Configuration File

    Structure:
      key1=value1
      key2=value2
      key3=value3
      key4=value4
      ...

    Example:
      DelayBetweenMoves=330
      SpeakDelay=10000
      AlwaysPerformFinisherAfterSetup=1
      TimeLimitOneFall=1200
      TimeLimitTwoOfThreeFalls=2700
      TimeLimitIronMan=3600
      WarGamesPeriodOne=300
      WarGamesPeriodOther=120

    Additional Information:
      You can also store options specific to your plugin in this file.
      However, we recommend using a configuration file of your own to allow
      the user to uninstall plugins without a trace. If you're writing a
      circuit plugin, the file can be found at ..\TNM.CNF. For regular
      plugins, it's at TNM.CNF.
      

