  14. *.IDX:
  ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
    Purpose:
      Index files which allow for quicker random access to the various
      databases.

    Structure:
      file position where record 1 starts
      file position where record 2 starts
      file position where record 3 starts
      ...
      file position where second-to-last record starts
      file position where last record starts

    Additional Information:
      All indexes start at a base of 0, i.e. when you open a file for random
      access, its position is assumed as zero. This is true for many
      programming languages. However, if the one you are using uses a base
      of 1, you need to add 1 to all index values to get the correct starting
      position.

      The wrestler database, for instance, is pushing 600k at the time this
      is being written. If you wish to access wrestler 845 of 846, you should
      definitely not read all 844 records before his comes. Since all
      wrestler records consist of 120 lines, you'd be reading a total of
      101,401 lines of data before you've retrieved the wrestler record you
      need.

      Obviously, this is far too slow. This is where the index files come in
      handy. Instead of going through the 844 records before the record you
      need, you simply open the index file first, go through the 844 record
      starting positions you need and retrieve the position where your record
      starts. Then you close the index file (if you don't need it anymore) and
      open the database you actually need. Do a SEEK to the record position
      you retrieved from the index file and then you can immediately start
      reading the data of the record you want and need - and nothing else.

      This brings down the number of lines you have to read from 101,401 to
      965 - which means your code will work over 100 times faster !

      Take my advice and use the index files whenever possible. You won't
      regret it.

    Example:
      Let's assume you have a small wrestler database with only four
      wrestlers.

      The 120-line record for the first wrestler, Jimmy Snuka, will start at
      file position 5 (let's not forget that the first line in the file
      contains the number of wrestlers, hence the first record can't start at
      position 0). Let's also assume that all wrestler records are 600 bytes
      long - which is a fairly accurate number for most.

      This means that Rey Misterio Jr.'s record will start at position 605,
      The Warlord starts at position 1205 and Bill Goldberg is last starting
      at position 1805.

      Your WRESTLRS.DAT file looks like this:
            4
            Jimmy Snuka
            <119 other lines of data>
            Rey Misterio Jr.
            <119 other lines of data>
            The Warlord
            <119 other lines of data>
            Bill Goldberg
            <119 other lines of data>

      The index file, WRESTLRS.IDX, will have the following structure in
      this example:
            5
            605
            1205
            1805

    Step-By-Step Instructions On Using Indexes:
      0) your goal is to access record x in the data file
      1) open index file
      2) read x lines of data from the index file; the x-th line of data is
         the starting position of record x in the database; we'll call it
         start_pos
      3) close the index file
      4) open the data file
      5) seek to position start_pos in the data file
      6) the file will not be at the position where record x starts
      7) read record
      8) close data file

      Obviously, if you need to access multiple wrestlers out-of-order, it
      is a good idea to read the contents of the index file into an array in
      memory and keep referencing that instead of opening the index file
      each and every time you need to access something.

    Sample Implementation In BASIC:

      function seekRecord&(byval database$,byval recordnumber)
      ' database$ is the base file name for a database, e.g. WRESTLRS,
      ' MOVES, MANAGERS, STABLES etc
      ' recordnumber is the number of the record you wish to access
      '
      ' seekRecord& returns an open file number which points to the
      ' start of the record you wish to access
      '
            f=freefile
            open database$+".idx" for input as#f
            g=freefile
            open database$+".dat" for input as#g
            input#g,nrofrecords
            if recordnumber>nrofrecords then
                  close#g
                  close#f
                  function=-1 ' return no pointer if the number of available
                              ' records is smaller than the record you want
                              ' to retrieve
            end function
            for a=1 to recordnumber
                  input#f,index
            next
            close#f
            seek#g,index
            function=g
      end function

    Sample Code For Using seekRecord&():
      deflng a-z
      database$="WRESTLRS" ' use wrestler database
      do
            input "What record number do you want to access ? ",r
            if r=0 then exit do
            f=seekRecord(database$,r)     ' open database and go to right
                                          ' position
            if f=-1 then                  ' record didn't exist
                  print "Sorry... record doesn't exist."
            else
                  line input#f,x$
                  print "First line of record is: "x$
            end if
            close#f                       ' close database
      loop


