 º±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±  Where We're Heading  ±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±±º
 ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼

   As has been indicated already, this is not the end of the road. The
   Plugin Interface will improve constantly as long as there is demand
   for it to improve.

   For instance, I will be adding a registration scheme which plugin
   authors can use to sell their plugins to users. It'll take care of
   generating registration codes and validating them - a quite touchy
   subject if you're not doing it completely professionally.

   To this day, there is no key generator for TNM V6.2plus or TNM 7 and
   for good reason: the algorithms used for generation and validation are
   completely waterproof.

   Obviously, a long time was spent and a lot of know-how was invested into
   developing them.

   Thus far, TNM 7's Plugin Interface does not allow for commercial plugins.

   One of the next releases of the Interface will contain code to handle
   just that.

   What is the point I'm trying to make ?

   TNM 7 will contain a version file in the future where it notes which
   version of the Plugin Interface is installed.

   This file will reside in DATA\PLGCVERS.DAT and you, as a plugin developer,
   should equip the plugins you are writing *today* to support version
   control.

   I recommend checking if DATA\PLGCVERS.DAT (..\DATA\PLGCVERS.DAT for a
   circuit plugin) exists. If not, it's safe to say that the Interface
   version is 1.1 or lower.

   If it does exist, open the file and read the one and only line in it
   which'll be a floating point number (e.g. 1.2). If your plugin was
   written for a later version of the Plugin Connector, then display a
   message that it won't run and quit immediately.

   For instance, if you write a commercial plugin and want to use TNM 7's
   registration scheme for it, and TNM 7 only starts supporting commercial
   plugins with Interface version 2.1, then check the PLGCVERS.DAT file
   to come up with the installed version.

   If you find out that the installed version doesn't yet support commercial
   plugins, exit gracefully to protect your property.

   Again, please let me stress that it is *your* responsibility to make sure
   your plugins know when to exit in order to not ruin anything.
 
   A second thing which I want to add eventually is support for new match
   types like the Brawl For All plugin Mike Sweetser currently is working
   on. They'll only be a hit if they integrate into TNM 7 seamlessly. We
   can't expect the user to enter the wrestlers' names manually.

   There are certain mountains which I'll have to climb before this feature
   can be implemented but it is possible and you can rest assured it will
   not be forgotten.



